The Environmental Protection Agency followed a similar path. The agency eliminated its research and development office and began laying off thousands of staff, citing savings of $750 million and a Supreme Court ruling that eased federal downsizing. The move hollowed out the EPA\'92s scientific core while leaving program offices to carry on with less independent knowledge. In parallel, the agency extended compliance deadlines for coal ash management and rescinded a $20 million grant meant to bring clean water to pesticide\uc0\u8209 contaminated rural communities in California, dismissing it as a \'93wasteful DEI program.\'94 These decisions did not abolish environmental regulation outright, but they shifted its center of gravity toward industry convenience and away from public health. The pattern was clear and deliberate.\
