The Department of Agriculture announced its own restructuring: salary cuts and the relocation of thousands of Washington\uc0\u8209 based staff to five other cities, closing key offices in the process. Officials framed the changes as fiscal prudence and footprint reduction, but the effect was to disperse and weaken a workforce that supports farmers, food safety, and rural communities. Taken together, the State, EPA, and USDA moves deepened the trait the Clock tracks as civil service politicized or privatized. Career officials became easier to purge, expertise easier to sideline, and the line between policy and ideology thinner. Stewardship of institutions for future generations gave way to short\u8209 term budget claims and culture\u8209 war priorities. The state\'92s capacity was treated as expendable.\
