Inside this expanding system, conditions were grim. Reports from Florida\'92s \'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94 camp described \'93torturous\'94 overcrowding, fungus, mosquitoes, and lack of food and medical care. Videos from a New York City confinement center showed detainees sleeping on floors near toilets after court appearances, held for long periods in rooms that ICE insisted were only for \'93processing.\'94 Human Rights Watch and other groups documented shackling, kneeling to eat, and denial of care in Florida facilities. ICE confirmed that it was using Medicaid data to track undocumented immigrants, after the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services signed an agreement granting access to the personal records of nearly 80 million recipients. The agency also continued to allow agents to wear masks during raids, over the objections of 21 state attorneys general who warned that anonymity fostered abuse and impersonation. Surveillance rose as accountability fell.\
