Individual stories brought these structures into focus. Mario Guevara, a Salvadoran journalist known for covering immigration enforcement, remained in ICE detention despite dropped charges from a protest arrest; his phone had been seized and its whereabouts were unknown. An Afghan translator who had worked for the U.S. military was detained in Connecticut after a routine biometrics appointment, despite a judge\'92s stay. A 25\uc0\u8209 year\u8209 old Cuban asylum seeker named Jenny was taken by masked agents in a San Antonio courtroom immediately after a hearing that had set a future date for her case. In Los Angeles, ICE arrested nearly 3,000 people in a matter of weeks, many with no criminal history, prompting the Catholic archdiocese to deliver food to families afraid to leave their homes. The security forces that the Constitution imagines as protectors of the people were, in these cases, aligned with the preservation of a particular political project. Protection and persecution traded places.\
